ts_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/WestLangley","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEwMDAwMTc=","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"WestLangley","type":"User","id":1000017,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/orgs"}},{"index":4,"author_association":"COLLABORATOR","body":"> If you were determined to do it, I would create BufferGeometry.toIndexed(), instead.\r\n\r\nThe reason I'm suggesting it here is that FBX is already storing data in an indexed format, at least for vertex positions. Every mesh geometry has at least these two properties:\r\n\r\nhttps:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/blob\/05d67e9fb68e19adb17400d32e4964f1debd52cd\/examples\/js\/loaders\/FBXLoader.js#L669-L670\r\n\r\nThings get a bit more complex for other properties (material indexes, normals, uvs etc) which can be stored in a few different ways (combinations of indexed or direct and per vertex, per polygon or per polygon vertex).","created_at":"2017-11-03T00:20:39.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/12560#issuecomment-341595780","id":341595780,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/12560","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDM0MTU5NTc4MA==","updated_at":"2017-11-03T00:20:39.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/341595780","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/looeee\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/looeee\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars2.githubusercontent.com\/u\/5307958?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/looeee","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/looeee\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/looeee","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/looeee\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjUzMDc5NTg=","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/looeee\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/looeee\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/looeee\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"looeee","type":"User","id":5307958,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/looeee\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/looeee\/orgs"}},{"index":5,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"@looeee I believe now that it is pointless to ask people to do the opposite of what they want to with their project, just look:\r\n> three.js is not modeling software.\r\n\r\n\ud83d\ude1b\r\nespecially when you can't really offer the solution that will make everyone happy. so when I need controversial feature like original inidces I just use old loaders from git history, or hack the code. so, for your question, why dont you just make sure that indices will be easy for interested people to hack in, and leave it at that?","created_at":"2017-11-03T04:58:27.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/12560#issuecomment-341622794","id":341622794,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/12560","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDM0MTYyMjc5NA==","updated_at":"2017-11-03T04:59:03.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/341622794","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/makc\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/makc\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars0.githubusercontent.com\/u\/242577?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/makc","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/makc\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/makc","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/makc\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjI0MjU3Nw==","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/makc\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/makc\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/makc\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"makc","type":"User","id":242577,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/makc\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/makc\/orgs"}},{"index":6,"author_association":"COLLABORATOR","body":"@makc I was just asking this question to try and understand whether it's worth the effort to try and make the FBXLoader return indexed buffer geometry. From my understanding, indexed geometry has two advantages: \r\n\r\n* lower memory requirements \r\n* faster vertex shader since there are potentially a lot less vertices to do the operations on \r\n\r\nHowever I don't know if there are corresponding disadvantages (aside from the obvious one that the code is more complex to write), hence asking this question. \r\n\r\nAside from that, I agree with the statement that three.js is not modelling software and shouldn't try to be \ud83d\ude1b \r\n\r\n@WestLangley I think you are suggesting something different here - I want to create an indexed buffer geometry directly, not via an unindexed geometry which I then convert, since it appears that the information to do so is already contained in the FBX format.\r\n\r\nI would need to investigate further to see whether this is actually possible, and I'm just wondering if this is something that is desirable before I go ahead and do that. If it's a bad idea for some reason then I would be better to spend my time improving some other part of the loader instead. ","created_at":"2017-11-03T05:10:37.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.